{
  "level": "A1–B1",
  "intro": "This topic gives you the <strong>grammar foundation</strong> for English: parts of speech, sentence structure, sentence types, imperatives, conjunctions and basic word order.",
  "rules": [
    {
      "label": "Parts of Speech",
      "color": "emerald",
      "text": "Words play different roles in a sentence:",
      "example": "noun, verb, adjective, adverb"
    },
    {
      "label": "Sentence Basics",
      "color": "blue",
      "text": "English sentences rely on a clear core structure:",
      "example": "Subject + Verb + Object"
    },
    {
      "label": "Word Order",
      "color": "amber",
      "text": "The Word Order lessons show how sentence position changes the pattern:",
      "example": "statements, questions, adverbials, emphasis"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "title": "1. What this topic covers",
  "intro": "These are the grammar points that usually come first in English:",
  "items": [
    {
      "label": "Parts of Speech",
      "title": "Parts of speech",
      "subtitle": "The basic roles of words: nouns, verbs, adjectives, adverbs and more."
    },
    {
      "label": "Sentence Structure",
      "title": "Sentence structure",
      "subtitle": "The simplest sentence model and the SVO pattern."
    },
    {
      "label": "Sentence Types",
      "title": "Sentence types",
      "subtitle": "Statements, questions, negatives and imperatives as core sentence models."
    },
    {
      "label": "Word Order",
      "title": "Word order",
      "subtitle": "A focused path through statements, questions, adverbials, objects and emphasis."
    }
  ]
}

{
  "title": "2. How to study this topic",
  "sections": [
    {
      "label": "Foundation",
      "color": "emerald",
      "description": "Start with <strong>Parts of Speech</strong> and <strong>Sentence Structure</strong> so you can see word roles and the sentence frame.",
      "examples": [
        {
          "en": "The student reads a book.",
          "ua": "Subject + verb + object."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "label": "Core models",
      "color": "blue",
      "description": "Then move to <strong>Sentence Types</strong>, <strong>Imperatives</strong> and <strong>Conjunctions</strong> to see how sentences change their function.",
      "examples": [
        {
          "en": "Open the window. / I was tired, so I stayed home.",
          "ua": "Imperative form and a basic link between clauses."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "label": "Word Order",
      "color": "amber",
      "description": "<strong>Word Order</strong> shows where words go in English and how position affects meaning.",
      "examples": [
        {
          "en": "She often works at home. / Do you work here?",
          "ua": "Focus on word position."
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}

{
  "title": "3. In short",
  "items": [
    "<strong>Parts of Speech</strong> helps you see what each word does in a sentence.",
    "<strong>Sentence Structure</strong> and <strong>Sentence Types</strong> give you the main sentence models.",
    "<strong>Imperatives</strong> and <strong>Conjunctions</strong> show how sentences work in real speech.",
    "<strong>Word Order</strong> helps you place words in natural English order.",
    "Together, these lessons give you a base for the rest of the grammar guide."
  ]
}
